The Great American Coffee Taste Test¶

In 2023 James Hoffman surveyed 4000 US residents to understand how they enjoyed coffees A, B, C and D. He also asked some questions about their coffee consumption habits and some basic demographic data.

Watch James discuss his survey and the results here. You can download the .csv of responses here.

The Coffees¶

Coffees A (light), B (medium), and C (dark) were all washed coffees but differed by roast level. Coffee D was a naturally processed single estate coffee from Colombia with more fruity, fermented flavours.

Coffees B and C are what many people would consider "normal" coffee, darker roast flavours of chocolate and nuts. Coffee A was a light roasted Kenyan coffee with fruitier, more acidic flavours that are increasingly popular in the 21st century.

Coffee D may be a totally new experience for some people because of the high level of fermentation and unusual variety.

All the coffees were delivered as frozen extracts delivered by Cometeer, designed to be melted in hot water by respondents. This way everyone gets a near identical experience because the participants are not brewing the coffee themselves.

My primary goal in this analysis is to answer 2 questions:

  • What is this coffee like?
    • How does it taste? How much do people like it?
  • How does preference differ among different consumers?
    • Can we identify a coffee everyone likes?

def colToCloud(col):
    """This function takes a column like a_notes where every cell is a string. 
    It removes any special characters and creates a dictionary where keys are words in the column and values are frequency.
    The dictionary ignores any common words that would not add meaning to a word cloud.
    The function returns a wordcloud object using the dictionary, in the shape of a coffee bean. """
    
    forbidden = { 
        "a(?:n|nd|s|t)?", "best", "better","the", "to(?:o)?", "in", "for", "o(?:f|r|n|ne|ut)?", "by", "with", "is(?:nt)?", "tha(?:t|n)?",
        "be", "this", "very", "like(?:s|d)?", "but", "bit", "finish", "was(?:nt)?", "coffee(?:s)?", "just", "have", "milk",
        "roast","me", "my", "some(?:thing)?", "i(?:t|ts|n|d)?", "when", "little", "more", "slight", "had(?:nt)?", "cool(?:ed)?", "really", "feel", "not(?:e|es)?", 
        "which", "did(?:nt)?", "favorite(?:s)?", "mine", "won", "maybe", "flavor","good", "bad", "could(?:nt)?", "would(?:nt)?", 
        "got", "get", "way", "over", "less", "least", "up", "most(?:ly)?", "enjoy(?:ed|able)?", "most", "all", "after", "diner", "nice(?:r)?",
        "tast(?:ing|e|er|ed|es)?", "almost", "just", "also", "down", "b", "much", "thin(?:ner)?", "hot(?:ter)?", "bod(?:y|ied)?",
        "no(?:t)?", "fe(?:el|els|lt)?", "lo(?:w|t)?", "prefer(?:ence)?", "slight(?:ly)?"
    }

    freqDict = {} 

    #Convert the column to a clean string
    colStr = col.dropna().str.cat(sep=' ').lower() 
    colStr = re.sub("\\'|’",'',colStr) 
    colStr = re.sub('\\n|\/|[^\w\d\s]',' ', colStr) 
    
    for word in colStr.split(' '):  
        word = word.strip()
        if any(re.match(f'{badword}$', word) for badword in forbidden): #Ignore forbidden words
            continue   
        val = freqDict.get(word,0) 
        freqDict[word] = val + 1   #Increase frequency count by 1

    bean_mask = np.array(Image.open("data/coffee.png")) #bean shape for cloud 

    wc = WordCloud(background_color="white", max_words=1000, mask = bean_mask, colormap='copper') # generate word cloud
    return wc.generate_from_frequencies(freqDict)
  
    acid.coffee = acid.coffee.map(lambda x: x[0].upper()) #e.g. b_acidity --> B
    
    #create long format df with variable (e.g. b_bitterness), and value (corresponding bitterness score)
    bitter = pd.melt(df.filter(like='_bitterness'), value_name='bitterness') 
    bitter.variable = bitter.variable.map(lambda x: x[0].upper()) 
    
    #concatenate column-wise, just taking the values from bitter i.e. the corresponding bitternesses
    return pd.concat([acid,bitter.bitterness],axis=1).rename({'variable':'coffee'}, axis=1)

def colToValuePercentage(groupcol,valcol,df):
    """Takes a col to be grouped by, and a col to supply value counts of each group.
    Returns seaborn-friendly df. Columns containing: group, value, percentage this value makes up of group."""
    
    df = df.groupby(groupcol,as_index=False)[valcol].value_counts(normalize=True).rename({'proportion':'percent'}, axis=1)
    df.percent*=100
    return df.round(2)

def boolcolsToPercentage(boolcols, df, groupcol=False):
    """This function takes a df, a list of boolean columns, and an optional column to groupby.
    If groupcol==False, a series containing the percentage of True values for each boolcol is returned.
    If groupcol, a df containing the percentage True of each boolcol in each group is returned"""
    
    if groupcol:
        grouped = df.groupby(groupcol)[boolcols]
        grouped_freq = pd.concat([grouped.sum(),grouped.size()],axis=1).rename({0:'count'}, axis=1)
        grouped_pct = grouped_freq.div(grouped_freq['count'],axis=0).mul(100)
        return grouped_pct.drop('count',axis=1)
    else:
        df = df[boolcols]
        return (df.sum()/len(df)).mul(100).sort_values(ascending=False)

def acid_bitter(df):
    """ This function takes a dataframe containing _acidity and _bitterness columns
    It returns the information in a long form df with columns: coffee, acidity, bitterness"""
    
    #create long format df with variable (e.g. a_acidity), and value (corresponding acidity score)
    acid = pd.melt(df.filter(like='_acidity'), value_name='acidity', var_name='coffee')
    acid.coffee = acid.coffee.map(lambda x: x[0].upper()) #e.g. b_acidity --> B
    
    #create long format df with variable (e.g. b_bitterness), and value (corresponding bitterness score)
    bitter = pd.melt(df.filter(like='_bitterness'), value_name='bitterness') 
    bitter.variable = bitter.variable.map(lambda x: x[0].upper()) 
    
    #concatenate column-wise, just taking the values from bitter i.e. the corresponding bitternesses
    return pd.concat([acid,bitter.bitterness],axis=1).rename({'variable':'coffee'}, axis=1)

Transforming Brew Method Data¶

There is a serious oversight in the questionnaire: The omission of AeroPress as a brew method. Unfortunately, because Other Methods is free text, there are a variety of spellings and spacings.

I have corrected this oversight, using regex to identify aeropress and moka users, creating their entries in new aero_user and moka_user columns and removing them from the othermethod_user column.

I have also created a column for people with no brewmethod:non_user

Now we can see aeropress is actuall the 6th most popular method, something we would have totally missed otherwise.

In [3]:
olddf=gactt_clean.copy()
old_brew_cols = olddf.filter(like='_user').columns #for showing before and after

aeropattern = r'(?i)\bAero\s*press?\b|\bAreo\s*press?\b'
mokapattern = r'(?i)\bMoka\s*pot\b|\bMokaPot\b|\bMokka\b'

gactt_clean['aero_user']=gactt_clean.othermethods.str.contains(aeropattern,regex=True)    
gactt_clean['moka_user']=gactt_clean.othermethods.str.contains(mokapattern,regex=True)

#remove aeropress and moka users from other_methoduser
gactt_clean.othermethod_user = gactt_clean.othermethod_user.mask(gactt_clean.aero_user | gactt_clean.moka_user, False) 

gactt_clean['nomethod_user']=gactt_clean.brew_method.isna()

Adding some numeric columns¶

For some numeric columns e.g. age, numeric ranges have been given as string, not numeric.

We need to create numeric columns with values that correspond to the ranges. We need these for visualisations and ordering, while retaining a list of the unique values in the original column to be used as labels.

Now for age there will be 2 columns: age: ["25-34","18-24",">65"...] and age-num:[30,20,70...].

1. What's this coffee like?¶

In this section we explore the tasting notes, the balance of acidity-bitterness. Then ask: which coffee is the most popular?

Back to the top

Tasting notes¶

All the respondents were asked to describe the tasting notes of the coffees in their own words. Here I use word clouds to give a sense of the most common attributes of each coffee.

In [7]:

b_cloud = colToCloud(tasters.b_notes)
c_cloud = colToCloud(tasters.c_notes)
d_cloud = colToCloud(tasters.d_notes)
clouds = [a_cloud,b_cloud,c_cloud,d_cloud]
In [8]:
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2,2,figsize=(10,15))
loop_dict = dict(zip([0,1,2,3],['A (washed light roast)','B (washed medium roast)','C (washed dark roast)','D (experimental natural process)']))
i=0
for ax in axs.flatten():
    ax.imshow(clouds[i],interpolation='bilinear')
    ax.axis('off')
    ax.set_title(loop_dict[i])
    i+=1

fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0)

This is great! We can see that our respondents have definitely identified characteristics we would associate with each coffee, and given us extra information about tasting notes.

People had a wide variety of responses, but some flavours really stand out.

  • A (washed light roast Kenyan) - this coffee is fruity and bright, people got the acidic notes of citrus, apple, berries as well as more classic nutty chocolate flavours.

  • B (washed medium roast blend) and C (washed dark roast blend) - these coffees had similar responses - those classic darker roast notes of chocolate, nuts, caramel. We can see some unambiguously negative responses starting creep in as well, a few people said B and C were boring or bland.

  • D (experimental natural process) - this coffee had more "complex", "interesting" flavours. It was very fruity, but in a different way to Coffee A, a lot of people identified a blueberry flavour. Respondents also + identified the weirder funky, fermented, alomsot wine like flavours.

This method needs a bit of tweaking to remove irrelevant words and join lemmata e.g. (all counts for "fruit" joined with those for "fruity"), but it is a great way of visualising the flavours of these coffees at a glance.

Acidity Bitterness Matrix¶

Respondents were asked to rate each coffee on how bitter and acidic they were on a scale of 1 to 5.

These are defining flavour characteristics in all coffee and too much of either can be overwhelming and, frankly, disgusting:

  • bitterness is associated with flavours like nuts and chocolate, bitter coffee tends to be darker roasted
  • acidity is associated with flavours like citrus, green apple, or tart berries, it tends to be lighter roasted

These flavours are also highly dependent on how the coffee is brewed, but we don't have to worry about that as the samples were pre-brewed, frozen, and sent out so everyone had the same tasting experience.

In [9]:
abm = sns.displot(acid_bitter(tasters), x='bitterness', y='acidity', col = 'coffee', discrete=True, col_wrap=2, color = '#8f3371')
abm.figure.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.25, hspace=0.25)
for ax in abm.axes.flatten():
    ax.tick_params(labelbottom=True, labelleft=True)
    ax.set_xlabel('bitterness', visible=True)
    ax.set_ylabel('acidity', visible=True)
abm.set_titles(col_template="Coffee {col_name}");

These are bivariate histograms: the darker the square the more respondents there are at those coordinates. For example, many people marked Coffee A as 2/5 bitterness, 4/5 acidic.

Coffees B and C were pretty similar, having an inoffensive but potentially boring of being low acidity and medium bitterness.

On first look, A and D are similar too having low bitterness and high acidity. When we look closer, we see that D tended a bit more acidic than A.

Most Popular?¶

In [10]:
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(15,5))
sns.set_style('darkgrid')
sns.set_palette('tab10')
sns.countplot(data=tasters.sort_values('abcd_preference'), x = 'abcd_preference', stat = 'percent',
              ax=axs[0], hue = 'abcd_preference', legend=False)
sns.violinplot(data = tasters.filter(like='_rating'),ax=axs[1])
axs[0].set_title(f'"Which coffee is your favourite?"({tasters.abcd_preference.count()} responses)')
axs[1].set_title('Rating distribution')
axs[1].set_xticklabels(['Coffee A','Coffee B','Coffee C','Coffee D']);
axs[0].set_xlabel('Preference')
axs[1].set(ylabel='Rating /5');

Coffee D appears to be the clear winner! Hurrah for natural processed coffee.

It is most frequently named as the favourite coffee, and it's ratings are largely higher than the others.

However, it is clearly not universally liked, otherwise it wouldn't have any low ratings. From the bulge at the bottom of the red violin plot we can see Coffee D has the highest number of 1/5 ratings.

Key finding: Coffee D is the most polarizing!

Although it has the most fans, it also has the most haters. It is marmite coffee.

If we look at the mean overall ratings, we see it is only very slightly higher than Coffee A.

In [11]:
display(tasters.filter(like='_rating').mean().to_frame().rename({0:'Mean rating /5'},axis=1).round(2))
Mean rating /5
a_rating 3.31
b_rating 3.07

A, B, and C are more commonly given mid-range ratings, they are crowd pleasers, especially A. When we think about the types of coffee we have it makes sense:

  • A, B, and C are "normal" coffees just with different levels of roast
  • A is a light roast, giving those fruitier tasting notes that are clearly popular in our sample
  • D is a naturally processed coffee.
    • Without getting too complicated, this imparts sweet fruity flavours, but also some fermented, "funky" flavours which some people really hate.

It will be interesting how these results are affected when we start focussing on respondents differentiated by coffee drinking habits and other factors, like age and gender.

Oh dear!¶

Our data set is skewed. The respondents are majority white males, mainly between the ages of 25 and 34.

There is less of a skew when it comes to favourite drink, but we should be aware of the high numbers of respondents whose favourite drink is pourover (27%). This was a surprising result in James Hoffman's opinion, and I agree. It reiterates that these respondents are not average consumers and many of them are going to have an appreciation for more experimental, complex coffees.

Let's look at how skewed demographics may have affected our conclusions about the most popular coffee, beginning with gender.

Men like coffees A and D, female preference is far more evenly distributed.¶

Our initial conclusion that A and D were the most popular coffees may have been misguided, the data has been totally skewed by the number of men and their preferences. Coffee B is very narrowly the favourite amongst women.

Let's take a closer look at the distribution of overall ratings given for each coffee by men and women.

    ax.set(yticks=range(0,6), ylabel='Overall rating /5', xticklabels=['A', 'B', 'C', 'D'], xlabel='Coffee')

Women hate coffee D more than they love it. Men really like it.¶

Look at the red violin plots, they show the density of ratings at each level and have a box-and-whisker plot at their heart showing the median and quartiles.

Females rated coffee D 1/5 more often than not, and way more than any other coffee. For men, it is the other way round: more than half of men actually rate D 4 or higher, and, althought they are more likely to rate it 1 than other coffee, it is much more marginally hated.

It is important to note that women also rated Coffee D 5/5 more frequently than any other coffee, reiterating it's polarising nature. Coffees A, B, and C were far safer bets, women are unlikely to hate them, but unlikely to love them either.

Coffees A and D decline in overall rating as respondents age, while Coffees B and C increase.¶

This makes sense, especially when we look at the proportion of roast preferences in the different age groups. As respondents get older appreciation of light roasts diminishes.

Older respondents react positively to more traditional, "normal" tasting coffee, reflecting their increased appetite for darker roasts.

Again the data is being skewed by one particular group: younger people.¶

Respondents aged between 25 and 44 rate coffees A and D highly, and they represent over 75% of respondents. Older consumers are far less likely to enjoy coffee D, but their opinion is not represented unless we look at the results by age.

5. Ethnicity¶

Back to the top

There is no significant relationship between ethnic background and coffee preference.

White respondents preferred Coffee D more often than other respondents but their preferences were not significantly different from Hispanic/Latino and Asian/Pacific Islanders. Together these 3 groups represent ~95% of respondents.

Looking at the chart on the left, one might argue that these groups skew the data because Black/African American respondents preferred C. But, in reality, it is irresponsible to infer preference based on ethnicity from such a small sample (there were only 39 respondents (~1%) who were Black/African American).

People who like less coffee flavour in their drink like coffees B and C more¶

People who like Espresso, Cortado, and Pour-overs are more likely to like coffee D. These drinks all tend to have more intense flavours. While latte and cappucino are heavily diluted by milk, espresso and cortado have no/little milk. Pour-over and regular drip are similar concepts, but pourover extracts more flavours (longer extraction time) without overextracting (lower temperature normally), resulting in the consumer getting a more flavourful coffee.

This is further evidenced by the fact that respondents who would normally add milk and sugar to coffee liked coffees B and C more.

It seems that the people who don't like a strong coffee flavour to their coffee prefer coffees B and C, while those who like pour-over or low milk drinks, appreciate coffees A and D more.

Most experts use espresso machines and pour-overs.¶

Inevitably this leads to higher equipment costs. But interestingly the more you spend on equipment, the more you spend on coffee in general i.e. investing in the ability to make coffee at home does not save money (I probably could have told you this from experience tbh).

There is a tight correlation between pour-over users and monthly spend, these are likely the same group who buy pour-overs at a cafe (expensive) and may well buy beans to use at home.

The correlation between espresso machine users and equipment spend is upsetting but inevitable.

Conclusion¶

We started with an analysis of the flavour profiles of each coffee before discovering that Coffee D is the most popular.

When we reviewed our respondents we found that our data was skewed in favour of young white males and we had a lot of pour-over fans as well. Analysis showed that these groups are the driving force behind Coffee D's high rating.

However, the analysis of expert opinion raised the question: is it young men skewing the sample? Or is it "experts", the vast majority of whom happen to be young and male?

Below, we analyse correlation between overall rating and other numerical data.

In [25]:
corr_cols=list(rating_cols)+['age_num', 'monthly_spend_num', 'expertise_selfeval']
#let's create a column which shows the degree of preference for D by calculating D rating - mean A B C rating
# tasters['ad_v_bc']= (tasters.a_rating+tasters.d_rating)/2 - (tasters.b_rating+tasters.c_rating)/2
tasters['d_pref_num']= tasters.d_rating - tasters[rating_cols[0:3]].mean(axis=1)

# and some separate dfs just containing certain demographic groups
female=tasters.loc[tasters.gender=='Female']
male=tasters.loc[tasters.gender=='Male']
old=tasters.loc[tasters.age_num>40]
young=tasters.loc[tasters.age_num<=40]

corrlabels=['A rating', 'B rating', 'C rating', 'D rating', 'Age', 'Monthly Spend', 'Expertise']
sns.set_style('white')
fig,axs=plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(15,6))
i=0
for df in [female,male]:
    corrdf=df[corr_cols].corr(method='pearson')
    mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(corrdf, dtype=bool))
    sns.heatmap(corrdf,cmap='vlag',center=0, annot=corrdf.round(2), mask=mask,ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set(xticklabels=corrlabels, yticklabels=corrlabels, title=df.gender.iat[0])
    i+=1

While there are no particularly strong correlations (near +/- 1), any stronger than +/- 0.2 are significant for our purposes.

We can see that for both men and women there was some positive correlation between A and D ratings, and negative correlation between D ratings and B/C ratings. If you like Coffee D, you are unlikely to like Coffee B, but you might like Coffee A.

While ratings correlate minimally with age or spend, the strongest predictor of a high D rating is level of expertise. There is also high correlation between spending and expertise.

So, it is too simplistic to say that men like this coffee and women don't, because there is a similar pattern of correlation in both female and male respondents. There are simply far more male respondents and their expertise is skewed higher. It is these experts skewing the results in favour of Coffee D.

In [26]:
sns.set_style('darkgrid')
fig,ax=plt.subplots(1,1,figsize=(10,7))
corrpal=[('Men','#e3685c'),('Women','#8f3371'),('Older (>45)','#1B4965'),('Younger (<45)','#5FA8D3')]
i=0
for df in [male,female,old,young]:
    sns.lineplot(df, x='expertise_selfeval', y='d_pref_num', errorbar='se', marker='o', ax=ax, label=corrpal[i][0], color=corrpal[i][1])
    i+=1

ax.set(ylabel= u'D Preference (D rating - µ(A,B,C ratings)', xlabel='Expertise(self-evaluated', xticks=range(1,11), title='Expertise x D Preference');

Where we have the most data we can see the smoothest trend towards higher expertise == higher D rating

This plot shows the relationship between expertise (x) and preference for coffee D (y) (calculated as D rating - µ(A, B,C ratings) among 4 different demographic groups.

The shaded areas show the standard error, you can see the margin of error is larger for the demographics where we have fewer respondents. We can see a lot of uncertainty around female expert opinion because very few female respondents marked themselves as highly expert.

For Male respondents and younger respondents (groups where we have the most data), there is a clear correlation between expertise and Coffee D rating. Respondents with less knowledge rate it below average but "experts" end up rating it ~1.3 above average.

Female respondents rate coffee D below average until their expertise level reaches 7 after which they rate it above average. But there is so much uncertainty (because of the small numbers of female respondents) that the correlation is less reliable. The female expert preference for Coffee D is more marginal and uncertain.

Uncertainty is high for older respondents but they do not exhibit high levels of preference for Coffee D. There is also a weak but noticeable negative correlation between age and Coffee D rating. We can say with more certaintly that older respondents do not like Coffee D in most cases.

Recommendations¶

If I was recommending which of these coffees a cafe should offer, I would still definitely say D should be on the menu.

It may be polarising, and unpopular among customers with less coffee experience, but it is interesting and something high-spending coffee connoisseurs will spend money on. Coffee D is best offered as a pour over, the favourite drink format of most of the people who like it.

But the cafe will still need a coffee for its espresso based drinks (latte, cappucino, flat white etc.), it could be Coffee B or C. I would recommend B, it is slightly more popular among women, latte/cappucino drinkers, and a few other groups. People who do not like D are likely to enjoy B.

With just these 2 coffees on the menu a cafe would have all their bases covered.
